    </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
        Of course, we also get an analogue of the isomorphism theorems for rings. We state them here without proof, and in somewhat terse fashion. Notice that some things are simplified by the fact that the normality issue does not arise (since <m>(R,+)</m> is an abelian group). 
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="th_ring_isom_theorems">
    <title>Isomorphism theorems for rings</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>R</m> be a ring.
    <ol>
        <li>
            <title>First isomorphism theorem</title>
            <p>
                Given a ring homomorphism <m>\phi\colon R\rightarrow S</m> with kernel <m>I=\ker\phi</m>,  we have <m>R/I\cong S</m> via the isomorphism <m>\overline{\phi}(r+I)=\phi(r)</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <title>Second isomorphism theorem</title>
            <p>
                Given a subring <m>S\subseteq R</m> and ideal <m>I\subseteq R</m>, <m>S+I</m> is a subring of <m>R</m>, <m>S\cap I</m> is an ideal of <m>S</m>, and <m>(S+I)/I\cong S/S\cap I</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <title>Third isomorphism theorem</title>
            <p>
                Let <m>\phi\colon R\rightarrow S</m> be a surjective ring homomorphism. If  <m>J</m> is an ideal of <m>R</m> containing <m>\ker \phi</m>, then <m>\phi(J)</m> is an ideal of <m>S</m>, and we have 
                <md>
                    <mrow>R/J \amp \cong S/\phi(J)</mrow>
                </md>.
                In particular, considering the quotient map <m>\pi\colon R\rightarrow R/I</m>, we see that if <m>I\subseteq J</m> is a chain of ideals in <m>R</m>, then <m>J/I</m> is an ideal of <m>R/I</m>, and we have 
                <md>
                    <mrow>(R/I)/(J/I)\amp \cong R/J</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <title>Fourth isomorphism theorem</title>
            <p>
                Let <m>\phi\colon R\rightarrow S</m> be a surjective ring homomorphism. The map 
                <md>
                    <mrow>J \amp \mapsto \phi(J)</mrow>
                </md>
                is a bijection between the set of ideals of <m>R</m> that contain <m>\ker\phi</m> and the set of ideals of <m>S</m>, with inverse given by 
                <md>
                    <mrow>J'\subseteq S \amp \mapsto \phi^{-1}(J')</mrow>
                </md>.
                Moreover, this bijection preserves just about all ideal operations and relations: <eg/>, inclusion, intersection, sum, product, <etc/>.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
    <p>
    </p>
    </proof>
    </theorem>
    
    
    

